# Folder Publish Guardrails

When the user asks to upload or push a specific folder, enforce a strict folder-scoped publishing workflow.

## Core rules

1. Scope first:
   - Explicitly confirm the exact folder(s) allowed to publish.
   - Treat all other folders as out of scope by default.

2. Use a clean publishing repo:
   - Create a temporary clean repository.
   - Copy only the approved folder(s) and required root metadata files.
   - Do not publish directly from a dirty monorepo root.

3. Validate remote target before push:
   - Confirm GitHub owner and repository name exactly.
   - Confirm repository exists or create it first.
   - Confirm authentication path (SSH key or token) is valid.
   - Do not assume username casing; verify real account slug.

4. Handle remote history safely:
   - If remote has existing commits and histories diverge, decide strategy:
     - preserve remote history: merge, then push
     - replace remote history with approved scope only: force push
   - Prefer `--force-with-lease` when replacing history.
   - If the remote has a platform-initial commit (for example only `LICENSE`), merge first unless user asks for strict replacement.

5. Verify result after push:
   - Check remote root file tree.
   - Confirm only approved folder(s) plus metadata are present.
   - Report final repository URL and latest pushed commit.

6. SSH/network reliability:
   - Prefer SSH over port 22 first, then use 443 fallback only when network requires it.
   - Avoid long blind waits; use bounded retries and explicit timeout.
   - Surface authentication or repository-not-found errors with concrete fixes.

## Operational checklist

- [ ] Target folder is explicitly defined.
- [ ] Clean publish repo is created.
- [ ] Only approved content is staged.
- [ ] Remote owner/repo is verified.
- [ ] Remote existence is verified.
- [ ] Push strategy is chosen safely.
- [ ] Remote content is verified post-push.
- [ ] Final URL + commit hash is reported.

## Never-do list

- Never push unrelated folders when user requested folder-only publishing.
- Never use blind waiting loops for network issues.
- Never assume GitHub username casing or repo existence without verification.
- Never force push without explicit scope-cleanup intent.
